It certainly seems like removing outliers for all variables does make a huge difference in terms of the skewness and the kurtosis, therefore, it is important to create a matrix without the outliers.

Trans_skew <- function(m = c(matrix)) {    
  i = 1
  while(i < 15){ 
skew = skewness(matrix[, i],na.rm=TRUE)
no_outlier_3<-  matrix[-c(which((abs(scale(matrix[,i])) > 1.959964))), c(1)]
skew_new = skewness(no_outlier_3)
kurt = kurtosis(matrix[, i], na.rm = TRUE)
kurt_new = kurtosis(no_outlier_3)
logged = log(no_outlier_3)
squared = (no_outlier_3)^2
root = (no_outlier_3)^(1/2)
reciprocal = (no_outlier)^(-1)
log_trans_skew = skewness(logged, na.rm=TRUE)
square_trans_skew = skewness(squared, na.rm=TRUE)
root_trans_skew = skewness(root, na.rm=TRUE)
reci_trans_skew = skewness(reciprocal, na.rm=TRUE)

log_trans = kurtosis(logged, na.rm=TRUE)
square_trans = kurtosis(squared, na.rm=TRUE)
root_trans = kurtosis(root, na.rm=TRUE)
reci_trans = kurtosis(reciprocal, na.rm=TRUE)


print(i) 
print("Skewness: (before and after)")
print(skew) 
print(skew_new)
cat("\n")
print("skewness:")
print("log transformation")
print(log_trans_skew)
print("square_transformation")
print(square_trans_skew)
print("square root")
print(root_trans_skew)
print("reciprocal transformation")
print(reci_trans_skew)
cat("\n")
print("Kurtosis: (before and after)")
print(kurt)
print(kurt_new)
cat("\n")
print("Kurtosis:")
print("log transformation")
print(log_trans)
print("square_transformation")
print(square_trans)
print("square root")
print(root_trans)
print("reciprocal transformation")
print(reci_trans)


cat("\n")
cat("\n")
cat("\n")
cat("\n")

  i = i + 1
  }
 
  }
